1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 { Declaration of a Closed Sicilian. Other options are 3. f4, which will be covered in the next chapter, and 3. Nf3, which tranposes back to the main lines below. } 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 (6. f4) 6... e5 { I recommend e5, setting up a Reversed Botvinnik setup. For a detailed analysis of this structure, see my English Opening guide! For a quick overview, the goal is to claim the center and the d4 square for the knight at the cost of allowing White to get the d5 outpost. } 7. Qd2 Be6 { I recommend the waiting move Be6 instead of the normal developing move Nge7 because White wants to play Bh6. Playing a waiting move forces White to reveal their next plan. } 8. Nge2 (8. h3 Nge7 9. Bh6 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Nd4 11. Qd2 Qb6 12. Rb1 O-O { f5 is coming up next with good pressure on all sides of the board } { [%cal Gf7f5] }) 8... Qd7 9. O-O h5 10. h4 (10. f4 h4 { Forcing open the h-file with a straightforward attack upcoming. }) 10... Nh6 11. f3 Nd4 { Black has a solid bind in the center, with a balanced position out of the opening. Plans include a pawn storm (either f5 or b5-b4 depending on how the game continues. White will try to kick back the Nd4 with c3, and try to get in a center break with d4. } *


