{ One of the openings I always had trouble against growing up. Higher rated players would play this aggressive opening against my Sicilian and I'd be lost by move 20. So I will teach you how to combat it and not repeat my mistakes. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. f4 Bg7 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 e6 6. O-O Nge7 { There are several ways for White to play aggressively. } 7. d3 (7. f5 d5 { An early f5 should be met with an immediate strike back in the center. } 8. fxe6 (8. exd5 exd5 9. Bb5 Bxf5) 8... dxc4 9. exf7+ Kf8) (7. Qe1 O-O 8. d3 d5 9. Bb3) (7. e5!? { Seems extremely challenging at first because the dark squares for Black are weak. Ne4 or Nb5 are coming up next with pressure on the f6 and d6 holes. However, Black has nothing to fear! } 7... d5 8. Be2 (8. exd6 Qxd6 9. Ne4 Qc7 10. Nxc5 Nd4! { And Black wins a minor piece }) 8... O-O 9. Nb5 f6) 7... O-O (7... d6?! { This is the move I'd always play when I was younger, and I'd get in trouble early on the kingside. Not a blunder in any way, but practically worse. } 8. Qe1 O-O 9. Qh4 a6 10. f5 exf5 11. Bg5 { And Black is tied down. Do not fall for this trap! Get an early d5 in! }) 8. Qe1 d5! { Shutting off the Bc4's diagonal once and for all. } 9. Bb3 Nd4 (9... Na5 { Another totally logical and playable move. } 10. Qh4 Nxb3 11. axb3 Nc6 12. Qg3 (12. Ng5 h6) 12... Nd4 { Also playable. White's attack is diminished without the light squared bishop. }) 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne2 a5 12. a4 dxe4 13. dxe4 b6 14. Ng3 Ba6 15. Rf2 Qd7 { With a pretty active position. Black should welcome any f5 pawn breaks by White. } 16. f5!? exf5 17. exf5 Nxf5 18. Nxf5 gxf5 { Although the pawn structure is a bit weakened, Black does have the open e-file now! Dynamic play coming ahead } *


