1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. c3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 d5 6. e5 Bg4 { Pinning the knight and looking to apply pressure on the d4 pawn with Nc6, Qb6, and Nh6-d5 potentially. } 7. Be2 (7. Bb5+ { The move that scores the best in practice. The idea is to immediately exchange on c6, leaving Black with a backwards pawn on an open file. } 7... Nc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nbd2 f6 10. h3 (10. exf6 exf6 11. O-O Ne7 { 0-0 next and Black should be okay. }) 10... Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Nh6 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 Nf7 { Black should aim to play Qb6 soon and pressure White's weaker pawns d4 and b2 }) 7... Nc6 8. O-O Nh6 9. Nc3 (9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nf5 11. Be3 e6 12. g4 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Qg5!? { An ambitious move to go straight for the king. f5 or h5 are threats in the near future } 14. Qe2 h5) 9... Nf5 { Threatening Bxf3 and Nfxd4 } 10. Be3 O-O 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 e6 { After getting rid of the light squared bishop, it is fine to place pawns on light squares. f6 next } 13. Qd2 (13. g4 Nxe3 14. fxe3 f6) 13... f6 { Basically forcing white to capture and leaving the d4 pawn exposed to attack from all sides of the board } 14. exf6 (14. g4 Nxe3 15. fxe3 fxe5) 14... Qxf6 15. Rad1 Ncxd4 *


