[UTCDate "2020.06.30"]
[UTCTime "11:24:56"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 { I know how tough this Qxd4 line is because I played it myself regularly on the White side! } 4... Nf6 5. e5 { The most demanding line, but Nc6 and Bb5 are also playable moves which we will analyze in this chapter. } (5. Nc3 { In my opinion, this is the best line since it pretty much forces Black to give up the bishop pair early on. } 5... Nc6 6. Qa4 d6 7. e5 dxe5 8. Nxe5 Bd7 { Practically forced or else the a4-e8 diagonal pin is too much pressure. } 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. Be3 Bg7 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Nb5!? (12. g3 O-O 13. Bg2 a6 14. O-O Rad8 { White is still better in this line, but Black shouldn't have anything severe to worry about. }) 12... Qe5 { Black's queen is surprisingly safe in the center }) (5. Bb5 { Threatening to take the knight when it lands on c6 to keep a powerful queen on d4 } 5... a6 6. e5 (6. Ba4 b5 7. Bb3 Nc6) 6... axb5 7. exf6 Nc6!? 8. fxe7 (8. Qh4 exf6 9. O-O d5 10. Re1+ Be6) 8... Qxe7+ 9. Qe3 Qxe3+ 10. Bxe3 b4 { Preventing Nc3 first! } 11. O-O Bg7 12. Re1 O-O { Long diagonal for the fianchetto bishop, and a nice bishop pair advantage in return for doubled pawns. Pretty nice! }) 5... Nc6 6. Qa4 (6. Qc3 Nd5 7. Qd2 Nc7) (6. Qf4 Nd5) (6. Qd1? Nxe5 7. Nxe5 Qa5+ { Black wins a pawn }) 6... Nd5 7. Qe4 (7. c4 Nb6 8. Qc2 Bg7 { With a fine position. White seems to have overextended a bit here. }) 7... Ndb4 8. Bb5 (8. a3 d5 9. exd6 Bf5 { See next chapter for the Trap! }) 8... Bg7 9. a3 Na6 { Trying to reroute the knight back to c7. } 10. O-O (10. Bxa6 bxa6 { Playable to destroy Black's pawn structure, but Black definitely has compensation with the light squares. } 11. O-O Bb7 { The h1-a8 diagonal is a nice source of attack in the near future, which should be an exciting game from here. }) 10... O-O 11. Re1 Nc7 { Balanced position } *


