1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Ng8!? { Yes, you saw that right. Knight retreats back to its original square 2 moves later. How can this be good, you may ask? Black's statement is that the e5 pawn is more of a liability for White than a strength. } 9. f4 (9. Bd4 Qa5) 9... Nh6 { The knight reroutes to f5. Black should utilize the open b-file to target the b2 pawn and then take advantage of White's overextension. } 10. Bd3 (10. Qd2 O-O 11. O-O-O d6!? { Sacrificing a pawn to open up the long diagonal } 12. exd6 exd6 13. Bd4?! (13. Qxd6 Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Nf5 15. Rd3 Ba6) 13... Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Nf5 15. Qd2 h5 { Creating an outpost on f5. } 16. Bd3 d5 { The next plan would be to play Rb8, Qa5, and rush an attack against the king. }) 10... d6 { Forcing open the long diagonal. } 11. exd6 (11. O-O O-O 12. exd6 exd6) 11... exd6 12. O-O Ng4 { The dark squares will be very vulnerable for White, especially on the g1-a7 diagonal. } 13. Bd2 O-O 14. h3? Qb6+ *


