1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. c4 { The other main popular 5th move, second to Nc3. } 5... Nf6 (5... Bg7 { A lot of theory has been developed for 5. Bg7 and it is still much more popular. }) 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 (7. Be3 Ng4) 7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 a5 { a5 is a multipurpose move:
1) To secure c5 as an outpost for the knight
2) To push the pawn up to a3 and open up the long diagonal
3) To play a4 + Qa5 and secure a square for the Queen. } 11. O-O a4 12. f3 Qa5 13. Rfd1 Be6 14. Rac1 Rfc8 (14... Rac8 15. Nd5! { See Important Theme #2 for details }) 15. Nd5 (15. b3 axb3 16. axb3 Qb4) 15... Qxd2 16. Bxd2 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Bd7 { Often times the position will simplify into an endgame. Black can try to play for an f5 break and has a comfortable endgame due to White's somewhat overextended pawns. } *


