{ A fairly standard position reached in the 4. Qc2 Nimzo. Instead of playing the common Bxc3, Black aims to give White an isolated d4 pawn }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 (9. Nxd4 { Nxd4 is possible of course, but this just shuts out the Bc1 and loses a center pawn for no good reason } 9... Nc6) 9... d5 10. a3 (10. cxd5 Nxd5) 10... Bxc3 11. Qxc3 (11. bxc3 { Also possible to avoid the isolated pawn, but the Be2 is overloaded! } 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Nc6 { Black will have plenty of play against White's double isolated f-pawns now }) 11... dxc4 12. Qxc4 Ba6 { With a nice endgame due to the isolated d-pawn for White. } *


