{ This game is a good example of how Black can attack on the kingside in the advance Caro-Kann instead of the more normal queenside breaks. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 h6 6. O-O Ne7 7. Nbd2 Nd7 8. Nb3 g5 { Very common plan to expand on the queenside. If White uses his resources to prevent c5, Black can switch gears and play on the kingside. } 9. a4 Bg7 10. a5 O-O 11. c3 Qc7 12. h4 g4 13. Ne1 h5 14. Nd3 Ng6 15. Nf4 Nxf4 16. Bxf4 f6 { Now the attack is forming, with an f-file about to open up. } 17. exf6 Qxf4 18. fxg7 Kxg7 19. Qc1 e5 20. c4 Be6 21. c5 a6 { Important to stop White's counterplay. If White gets to play a6 successfully, Black's pawn chain will be precarious. } 22. dxe5 Qxc1 23. Raxc1 Rf4 24. Rfd1 Nxe5 25. Rc3 Re8 26. Re3 Bc8 27. Nd4 Rff8 28. Bd3 Kf6 29. Kh2 Re7 30. Kg3 Rfe8 31. Bc2 Nd7 32. Rxe7 Rxe7 33. b4 Nf8 34. Kf4 Re5 35. f3 Ne6+ 36. Nxe6 Bxe6 37. Bg6 gxf3 38. gxf3 Bf5 39. Bxf5 Rxf5+ 40. Ke3 Ke5 { Again, we reach a better rook endgame for Black due to the more pawn weaknesses for White (h4, f3, and b4) } 41. Rg1 d4+ 42. Kf2 Kd5 43. Rg7 Kc4 44. Rxb7 d3 45. Rd7 Kc3 46. Ke3 Re5+ 47. Kf4 Re1 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


