1. c4 c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e5 { This leads to a familiar position: Botvinnik setup against the King's Indian with colors reversed! However, the extra tempo for playing White does make a difference if acted fast enough. } (5... d6 6. O-O Nh6 { See variation below. Once White castles, Nh6 comes and h4 is no longer a viable option. So what next? No fear, there is a solution } 7. d4 cxd4 8. Bxh6 Bxh6 9. Nxd4 { White loses the bishop pair, but the Bg2 has long range and quick development. Plus, the Bh6 for black is quite misplaced for now. } 9... Bd7 10. c5) (5... Nh6 { Nh6 with plans of Nf5 are quite annoying because it stops d4, and playing e4 yourself to kick the knight will only bring it to its dream outpost on d4. } 6. h4! { According to GM Marin, h4 is the way to punish an early Nh6 since Black cannot play the typical h5! Again, the common theme is to find the drawback in each other Black's moves and base a plan to exploit that drawback. } 6... Nf5 7. h5 d6 8. d3 Bd7 9. h6 Bf6 10. Ne4 { The h6 pawn acts as a thorn in Black's kingside. }) 6. a3 { Delaying 0-0 } 6... Nge7 (6... a5 { With knowledge of the gambit with 7. b4 below, it may be smart for Black to just prevent b4 altogether. } 7. O-O Nge7 8. Ne1 { Knight goes on a journey to the juicy d5 outpost! It is important to delay d3 (for now) } 8... O-O 9. Nc2 d6 10. Ne3 Be6 11. Ned5 Rb8 12. d3 h6 13. Rb1 Kh7 14. Bd2 f5 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 { White has achieved plenty of play on the queenside. }) 7. b4!? { The main idea here! Black is not ready to break open the position. There is a nice hole on d6 for White to take advantage of } 7... cxb4?! { Usually not good to accept the gambit. } (7... d6 8. O-O O-O 9. Rb1 { White does get quick play on the queenside. }) 8. axb4 Nxb4 9. Ba3 Nbc6 10. Nb5 O-O 11. Bd6 e4 12. Bc7 Qe8 13. Nd6 { Queen's trapped. Of course this does not end well for Black, but other tries will still torture black for the rest of the game. } *


