1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. Nc3 { While there are tons of possible setups for Black, I will only cover the two major ones: Bb4 and Bc5. My recommendations against these lines lead to pretty similar positions. } 4... Bc5 (4... Bb4 5. Nd5 Bc5 6. e3 { Sort of transposing back to the 4. Bc5 variation. } 6... O-O 7. Ne2 d6 8. O-O Nxd5 (8... Be6?? 9. d4 exd4 10. exd4 Bb6 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. d5) 9. cxd5 Ne7 10. d4 exd4 (10... Bb6 11. b3 f5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Bb2 { With pressure along both long diagonals }) 11. Nxd4) 5. e3 { I have had success with both 5. Nf3 and 5. e3, but e3 seems to be the more straightforward one, with the clear plan to shut off the Bc5's diagonal. } 5... d6 (5... d5!? { Scores well for Black in practice, so I will go over this line a bit. } 6. cxd5 Nb4 { You can see it's not really a pawn sacrifice. Black will regain the pawn on d5 since White cannot allow Nd3+ } 7. d4 exd4 8. exd4 Be7 (8... Bxd4? 9. Qa4+ { Fork! }) 9. Nge2 Nbxd5 10. O-O O-O 11. Nf4 c6 12. Nfxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qb3 { With a fairly balanced position, but having the initiative. }) 6. Nge2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 (7... Be6?? { This blunder occurs so often, even at the advanced level. Seems like normaly development, right? Wrong } 8. d4 { Fork coming right up }) 8. h3 Bh5?! 9. g4 Bg6 10. d4 Bb6 11. f4 { Punishing black for developing the light squared bishop too early. It gets trapped on its own territory! } *


