1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 { The Reversed Dragon, another very theoretical battle. It is heavily debated whether the extra tempo for White will create more chances, since it is often stated that the Accelerated Dragon does not offer Black many good winning chances. } (3... c6 { Another one of the lines I find annoying (and which I play myself as Black!). I've tried lots of different moves against the Reversed Alapin, and found d4 to be the most effective. } 4. d4 exd4 (4... e4 5. d5 { To not allow BLack to complete the pawn chain with d5 } 5... cxd5 6. cxd5 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ (7... Qa5 8. Nc3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qxd5 10. Qxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Bxe4 Rxg7 13. Bxd5 { White's up a clean pawn and has wide open lines. }) 8. Qxd2 O-O 9. Nc3 Re8 10. d6 { An interesting try to cramp Black's position, though it does allow Nc6 }) 5. Qxd4 d5 6. Nf3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qa4 Be6 11. Bf4 { Should not bring White a lot of trouble. Simply blockade the isolated d5 pawn and not overextend. }) 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nb6 6. e3 { 6. Nf3 is more mainstream, but this 6. e3 line is one of my pet lines. If Black has not seen this before, it would throw him off. Instead of Nf3, White develops with Nge2 followed by an early f4 to try to get 2 central pawns against none for Black. } 6... Nc6 7. Nge2 Be7 (7... h5 { I've faced an early h5 multiple times. The best bet is to strike back in the center and ignore the pawn. } 8. d4 h4 (8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. exd4 h4 11. O-O { This pawn is not to worry about. Black's king, on the other hand, is! } 11... hxg3 12. Re1+ Be7 13. hxg3) 9. d5 h3 10. Bf3 Qf6 11. Be4) 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 exf4 (9... f6 10. f5 Bd7 11. d4 exd4 12. exd4 Be8 13. d5 Ne5 14. Nf4 { Huge space advantage and a nice outpost on e6 to hop in anytime }) 10. Nxf4 Ne5 11. d4 Ng6 *


