1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Nge2 e5 (6... c5 { c5 Transposes to the c4 c5 lines part 2 }) 7. O-O Nc6 8. d3 Bg4 (8... Nd4 { Against an early Nd4, I recommend Nxd4 to play for either f4 or b4 and target the d4 pawn long term. } 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Ne2 c5 (10... Nd7 11. b4 a5 12. b5 Nc5 13. Bb2 Ne6 14. f4 { The d4 pawn will definitely be more of a weakness for Black than a thorn. }) 11. b4!) (8... Be6 9. h3 Qd7 10. Kh2 Nh5 (10... Ne8 11. f4 f5 12. Be3 Nf6 13. Nd5 { Qd2 followed by a queenside expansion is up next. }) 11. g4 { Black wants to play f5, but Nh5 is too ambitious. g4 forces the knight back. } 11... Nf6 (11... Nf4 12. Nxf4 exf4 13. Bxf4 { Interesting pawn sacrifice, but hard to find enough compensation for the pawn. } 13... f5 14. exf5 gxf5 15. g5 { Keep as many lines closed as possible. Do not allow Black's rook to become active. })) 9. f3 (9. h3!? { I do not recommend playing h3, even though it may be the more "obvious-looking" one if you have the Botvinnik structure (c4 and e4 pawns with a hole on d4) because Black will exchange bishop for knight and reroute a knight to d4. It can be annoying to deal with. } 9... Bxe2 10. Nxe2 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5,Gc5e6,Ge6d4] }) 9... Be6 10. f4 Bg4 { Yes Black could still come back and exchange, but hey, you got a free tempo with it! } *


