1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 d5 (3... c5 { This is the other main move, which frankly I have only faced once or twice in practice. 3. d5 is almost always the move. } 4. e5 { A sharp theoretical gambit line. I do not recommend it though as it's a very dynamic advantage which can easily be lost with small inaccuracies. } (4. Nf3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 { This leads to a Marcozy Bind setup, which is flexible. As a whole new opening, I won't explain it here. Play solid and slow, White should be fine always. } 6... Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 d5) 4... Ng8 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nxe5 8. Ndb5 { And loads of theory here. }) 4. e5 d4 { d4 is the main move, though I have seen Ne4 and Nfd7 plenty of times. } (4... Ne4 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. d4 Bb4 7. Qc2 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Be7 9. Bd3 { These positions lead to strong attacks on the kingside, while Black lacks development. }) (4... Nfd7 5. cxd5 Nxe5 6. d4 Ng6 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. Nf3 { See Chapter 36 for one of my games in this line. Ng6 is quite awkwardly placed. It is standard to be on f6, not g6. }) 5. exf6 dxc3 6. bxc3 Qxf6 7. Nf3 e5 (7... c5 8. Bd3 { Similar idea to the 7. e5 line. Complete development by placing the bishop on e4, Rb1, and 0-0. } 8... Nc6 9. Be4 h6 { Often played to stop d4 + Bg5, trapping the queen. } 10. O-O Bd6 11. Rb1 O-O 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Ba3) 8. Bd3 { The idea is to play Be4 next, and 0-0. Rb1 is always on the table with added pressure to b7. } 8... Nc6 9. O-O Bc5 10. Be4 O-O 11. Re1 { Bxc6 followed by Nxe5 is a strong threat. } *


