1. c4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 { Here, black has 2 main moves: e6 and g6. g6 often leads to Botvinnik English setups. See next chapter for the g6 lines. } 3... e6 4. Nf3 d5 5. O-O c6 { Black wants to play a Stonewall setup, but we do not allow it. Playing d4 transposes to a Stonewall, but we do not give up the e4 square for free. } 6. d3 Bd6 (6... Be7 { The better reply, but still awkward. } 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4 d4 9. Ne2 fxe4 10. dxe4 d3 11. Nf4 Nxe4 12. Nxd3 { Black's pawn structure will always be permanently damaged. }) 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4! { The go-to pawn break to refute the Stonewall against the English. Although it is a pawn sacrifice, Black's pawn structure is permanently damaged. } 8... fxe4 9. dxe4 Nxe4 (9... dxe4 10. Ng5) 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Ng5 { White will regain the pawn, get good development, and extra long term pressure against Black's isolated e6 pawn. } *


