1. c4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. d3 O-O 6. e4 d6 (6... fxe4 7. dxe4 d6 8. Nge2 c5 9. O-O Nc6 10. h3 { To prepare Be3 so Ng4 is not allowed } 10... e5) 7. Nge2 e5 8. O-O Nc6 9. Nd5 { The key move here. The Nd5 + Bg5 combo is essential to face this ambitious line. Often, you don't play the typical f4 break because the pawn structure is too symmetrical to fight for an advantage as White on the kingside/center. } 9... Be6 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. Qd2 Rae8 12. f3 { Keeping the center stable so White can focus on queenside expansion. } 12... Rf7 13. b4 *


