1. c4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3 d6 { This move signals the Classical Dutch instead of the Stonewall. One of the differences between the Classical Dutch and this position is White's d-pawn has not been pushed yet! This makes the standard Ne4 maneuver by BLack useless. } 7. b4 { Scoring well in practice. Instead of fighting in the center, White immediately expands on the queenside. Now, Black is virtually forced to push the e-pawn again, losing a tempo. } 7... e5 8. d3 { Transposing back to a very common c4 e5 line with a loss of tempo for Black. } 8... Qe8 9. b5 Nbd7 10. a4 { Once White's a-pawn reaches a6, it activates White's Bg2, which turns into a monster. } *


