{ This game illustrates the power of the bishop pair and what to do when you have a bishop pair vs your opponent's knight pair }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Bc4 Qb6 8. Bb3 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Kh1 Nc5 { Now the knight will be a pest to the Bb3. One of the major ideas of the Nbd7 line. } 11. f4 Qc7 12. Qe2 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Rad1 O-O 15. f5 Nxb3 16. axb3 Bd7 { Notice Dominguez Perez is playing very slowly with the bishop pair, careful not to push pawns too soon. If Black plays e5 at any time, d5 becomes a dream outpost for White's knights. } 17. Qd3 Rad8 18. Qh3 Qc5 19. Nde2 b5 20. Rd2 b4 { Forcing the knight to a more passive square } 21. Nd1 exf5 22. exf5 Rfe8 23. Ng3 Bb5 24. Rg1 Bd4 { Power of the bishop pair! } 25. Qg4 Bxg1 26. Nh5 Bd4 27. h3 Re1+ 28. Kh2 Be5+ { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


