1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 (2... g6 { Playing Kings Indian style with 2. g6 will lead to a Pirc, which is the worse version of the Kings Indian. I recommend simply d5, which simply reduces the effect of the Nc3. } 3. e4) 3. Bg5 (3. Bf4 g6 { Transposes to the d4 Nf6 Bf4 g6 Nc3 line - See below for detailed analysis }) 3... Nbd7 { Here there are usually two ways White can continue: either with f3 or Nf3. } 4. f3 { The more dangerous of the two. White prepares e4 next with the full center. I do not recommend a fianchetto here for that reason. } (4. Nf3 { This line is pretty harmless. White cannot get a pawn center with e4 anytime soon. } 4... g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. h3 b5 { Kind of a dull position here. Around equal. The Nc3 is awkwardly placed, so naturally b5-b4 is a plan to gain space and then hop in to e4. }) 4... h6 (4... g6?! 5. e4 { And white gets a lot of space before you get castled. Avoid!! }) 5. Bh4 c5 { It is often the case that an early f-pawn push from your opponent must be punished with a strike in the center. c5 accomplishes that } 6. e3 (6. e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 Qb6) (6. dxc5 e6 { The ugly f3 move comes back to haunt White. Black is better in any line here once the dark squares start opening up. Potential Qb6 and Bxc5 will be a nightmare for White }) 6... e6 { And it's hard for White to prove that an early f3 is a pro rather than a con here. Normal development should be fine for Black. Be on the watch for ambitious Qb6 ideas if the position calls for it. } *


