[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.19"]
[UTCTime "12:09:13"]

{ At first glance, the exchange variations may cause some Kings Indian players to groan in boredom since lower rated players can go for this line and achieve a minimum risk position to exchange off pieces. However, it is not completely symmetrical. Look at the pawn structure }
1. dxe5 dxe5 { The key, which is absolutely essential for any Kings Indian player, to note is that Black can take advantage of an outpost on d4 while White can't say the same about d5 (since Black can defend it with c6) } { [%csl Gd5,Gd4] } 2. Bg5 c6 3. Qc2 Qc7 4. Rad1 Nc5 { Now the plan is a bit clearer. Black's Nc5 is rerouting to d4 eventually through e6. Bg4 is also coming up in hopes to exchange bishop for knight. Black will end up with a beautiful outpost on d4 for the knight. White's Nc3 on the other hand is stuck finding a good outpost to play on } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gc5e6] } *


