1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 Nbd7 7. Nc3 e5 8. h3 (8. dxe5 dxe5 9. e4 c6 { Absolutely harmless. Qc7 next, followed by a well timed Nc5-e6-d4. See my game: Deshpande - He 0-1 sample game below for a sample }) 8... Re8 9. Be3 (9. e4 { e4 is commonly played here anyways, which will transpose to part 1. }) 9... exd4 10. Nxd4 (10. Bxd4 c5 11. Be3 Nb6 12. Nd2 Nh5 13. g4 (13. Kh2 Nxg3 { Nxg3 comes anyways } 14. Kxg3 Be5+ 15. f4 Bxc3) 13... Ng3! { White's Be3 has huge drawbacks clearly. }) 10... Nc5 11. b4 (11. Qc2 a5 { Maintaining the outpost on c5 }) 11... Nce4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 { Threat of Nxg3, winning a pawn. } *


[Event "🏆 King's Indian Defense Repertoire 🏆: White's double fianchetto"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/NlFMirvk/7nAmFVtx"]
[Date "2020.06.19"]
[Result "*"]
