1. c4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Nd2 c5 { A common theme you've seen is a race between Black's attack vs White's queenside expansion. With this in mind, c5 makes total sense. Why not slow down White's plan to an extreme first before starting your attack? } 10. Rb1 Ne8 11. b4 b6 (11... cxb4 12. Rxb4 f5 { The d6 pawn is backwards and may be a big target later on. }) 12. a4 f5 13. a5 Nf6 14. Qa4 Bd7 15. Qa3 Bh6 16. Bd3 Qc7 17. bxc5 bxc5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Bc2 a6 20. Nde4!? { Taking advantage of the fact that the Bh6 is loose } 20... Bxc1 21. Nxf6+ Rxf6 22. Rfxc1 Raf8 23. Rb6 Bc8 { Black has to make sure White's pieces don't invade. That means keeping a6 no matter what. Otherwise, Nb5 will come and the a-pawn runs. } 24. Ne2 f4 25. Be4 Nf5 26. Rc6 Qg7 27. Rb1 Nh4 28. Qd3 Bf5 29. Kh1 f3 30. Ng3 fxg2+ 31. Kg1 Bxe4 32. Qxe4 Nf3+ 33. Kxg2 Nd2 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


