[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bd2 O-O 7. g4 { If this move seems strangely familiar to you, then you must have watched Carlsen - Giri in the Magnus Carlsen invitational. g4 is a bold move that makes complete sense. White offers the g-pawn in order to gain full control on the g-file for the rook. If Black declines, then g5 to take advatnage of the h6 hook is quite strong. } 7... Nxg4 (7... Nbd7 { If Black declines the gambit, White will get g5 safely and also an open g-file. Lots of fun for White } 8. g5 hxg5 9. Bxg5 { [%cal Gh1g1,Gd1c2] }) 8. Rg1 *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 7) Sac to open up square"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/Jm5HFCTY"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "7) Sac to open up square"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/PVP1z86f"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/1b1nbppp/pn1pp3/1p4P1/3NPP1P/1P1B3R/P1P1NQ2/1KBR4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

1. f5 e5 2. f6! { A great in between move! Your knight is not forced to move just because it's attacked. If that was the case, the knight has nothing better than to just retreat to f3, and Black will continue with his initiative with d5. This in-between move frees up the key square f5 for the knight. A truly smart pawn sacrifice. } 2... gxf6 3. Nf5 { Not only does White achieve the beautiful knight outpost on f5, an attack is quickly forming on the now open g-file. } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 8) Nd5 sac in Sicilian"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/B1vdFYXw"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "8) Nd5 sac in Sicilian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/tzwz2GmT"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/1bq2ppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQR1K1 w kq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ This theme is very common in any Open Sicilians. In the majority of these cases, the knight sacrifice is not completely sound. But there is so much compensation that White often scores very well. A computer may defend as Black easily, but for any human player (including GMs), it is quite tough. }
10. a4 { Often common to play Nd5 after black plays b4 for the knight to hit another target. } 10... b4 11. Nd5! { If you haven't seen this sac before, this will look very dubious. It is indeed a long term advantage that White gains. Black more or less has to accept the sacrifice or else the knight will just sit there controlling all sides of the board. } 11... exd5 12. exd5+ Kd8 (12... Be7? 13. Nf5) 13. c3 { Now it is clear why the moves a4 b4 are inserted at the start! White can now create a pawn break on the queenside to open yet another file for a rook, the c-file! Bg5 and Rc1 will complete development while Black is completely tangled up. See https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1513377 for a sample game with the Nd5 sacrifice } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 9) Sac piece to open adjacent file"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/Ba2LVlAh"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "9) Sac piece to open adjacent file"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/RW3ed2IL"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp2bppp/2bppn2/q5B1/3NPP2/2NQ4/PPP3PP/2KR3R b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

12... h6 13. h4! { Again, we see the bluff concept at play. Black would love to push back the pesky Bg5, and White wants to keep it there. Therefore, h4 is a great move to keep the bishop on g5 and throw out a bluff. If Black dares to capture, the open h-file is quite deadly. Otherwise, White reaps all the benefits.. and more! g4 comes next and a pawn storm is on its way! } 13... Rfc8 { Smart to not accept the sacrifice } (13... hxg5?! 14. hxg5 Ng4 15. e5 g6 16. Qh3) 14. g4! { The threat is now Bxf6 followed by g5 to crack open the kingside. } *


