[Event "🏆 French Defense Repertoire 🏆: Theme #1"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/xSou7xMc/ALcBWsq0"]
[Date "2020.08.12"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defense Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "Theme #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/A4EBp7Ds/zk1whRCY"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.12"]
[UTCTime "20:52:17"]

{ Due to the relatively closed nature of the French Defense, understanding of pawn structure is extremely important. The first theme is "Attack the pawn chain at its base because it is the weakest". }
1... Qb6 { Hitting the current base of the chain (b2) } 2. Be2 Nge7 3. Na3 (3. O-O? { White is clearly oblivious of what's coming up next. } 3... cxd4 4. cxd4 Nf5 { There is a new base of the pawn chain: d4! Now either the d4 pawn or b2 pawn is lost for White. }) 3... cxd4 4. cxd4 Nf5 { Hitting the new base of the pawn chain, the d4 pawn. White can defend it with Nc2 though, and the game continues. However, this principle regarding pawn chains drives many of Black's middlegame plans. } *


[Event "🏆 French Defense Repertoire 🏆: Theme #2"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/xSou7xMc/fb13TLtk"]
[Date "2020.08.12"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defense Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "Theme #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/A4EBp7Ds/Lrn77O4k"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2PB4/PP1N1PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.12"]
[UTCTime "20:52:17"]

{ In contrast to Theme #1, attacking a pawn chain at its head can be beneficial to disrupt the chain and create open files and diagonals as a result of the pawn break. }
1... Nc6 2. Ne2 cxd4 3. cxd4 f6 { The f6 pawn break is ideal when White cannot comfortably keep up the pawn chain with f4. As a result, this forces White to concede with exf6 or enter some tactical complications as seen below. } 4. f4? (4. exf6 Nxf6 { Qxf6 is also playable. This leads to a theoretical main line of the French Tarrasch with 3. Nf6. This is not my recommendation in this repertoire, but it is sound and quite popular at all levels. }) 4... fxe5 5. fxe5? (5. dxe5 { Creating a new chain, but at the cost of severely weakening the g1-a7 diagonal, which Black can easily take advantage of with Bc5 and Qb6 in the near future }) 5... Nxd4!? 6. Nxd4 Qh4+ { Picking up a pawn in the process after Qxd4. } *


[Event "🏆 French Defense Repertoire 🏆: Theme #3"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/xSou7xMc/RfzMcv7Q"]
[Date "2020.08.12"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defense Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "Theme #3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/A4EBp7Ds/Mp0qXS78"]
[FEN "r1bq1k1r/pp1n1pp1/4p2p/3pP3/2pP4/2P2N2/P1PQBPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.12"]
[UTCTime "20:52:17"]

{ This is a typical pawn structure in the MacCutcheon French, which I recommend against the Classical Variation. White's doubled c-pawns is their only weakness, so naturally, Black's plan is to target them. }
1... Qa5 2. g4 Nb6 3. Qe3 Qa3 4. g5 Na4 { Pieces are piling up on c3, forcing the White king to walk to defend it. } 5. Kd2 b5 { It is now a race for Black's queenside play versus White's attempt to break open the kingside. See Romanov - Nepomniachtchi for the complete game. } *


[Event "🏆 French Defense Repertoire 🏆: Theme #4"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/xSou7xMc/n74P0X3l"]
[Date "2020.08.12"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defense Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "Theme #4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/A4EBp7Ds/TQzl4LLh"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pp2bppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/4P3/3P1NP1/PPPN1PBP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.12"]
[UTCTime "20:52:17"]

{ This is one of the defining setups of the Kings Indian Attack. The theme here is to delay castling in order to maintain flexibility for a potential kingside pawn storm. It can be quite deadly if White is not prepared for it }
1. O-O b6!? { Intentionally delaying kingside castling. As a friendly note: Castling is totally fine. This is just an interesting idea worth mentioning! } 2. Re1 Bb7 3. e5 Nd7 4. Nf1?! { White is unaware of any of Black's ambitions and continues playing Kings Indian attack style. This is where the surprise attack comes in. } 4... g5!? { A kingside pawn storm with h5 + g4 or h4 will break open the h- and g-files. Black typically follows up with 0-0-0 and utilizing the open files for an attack. Black scores quite well in practice. } 5. h3 h5 *


[Event "🏆 French Defense Repertoire 🏆: Theme #5"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/xSou7xMc/ZIrEApSj"]
[Date "2020.08.12"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defense Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "Theme #5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/A4EBp7Ds/C4fLu2fT"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2n1p3/3pPP2/2pP4/2N1BN2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.12"]
[UTCTime "20:52:17"]

{ This position arises in the Classical variation with 4. e5, where White castles long really early on. Here, you can punish White's early commitment of the king to the queenside with a nifty move: }
1... b5! { Gambiting a pawn to get a quick attack going. White has no good option. Accepting the gambit will give a strong initiative for Black after Rb8, while declining the gambit will just allow b4 next move. } 2. Nxb5 Rb8 3. Nd6 Bxd6 4. exd6 Nf6 { With a dominating position. It's quite surprising to me how common this mistake is in practice. See Classical Variation with 4. e5 part 2 below for a more detailed analysis. } *


