1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 { Often the plan of a lower rated player in order to simplify into a drawn endgame. With this in mind, my repertoire will involve a setup that avoids symmetry. } 3... exd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 { Already deviating from symmetry on move 4 } 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3 Bg4 8. Bg5 (8. Re1 Qd7 9. b4 O-O! { 0-0-0 would be just too risky since it walks right into White's queenside pawn storm. } 10. Bg5 Ng6 { Although the position is still somewhat symmetrical in terms of pawn structure, the piece imbalance allows for creative attacking play. }) 8... f6 9. Bh4 Qd7 10. Nbd2 O-O-O { 0-0-0 if White has played Bg5-h4 since you can speed up your kingside pawn storm while chasing the white Bishop. Otherwise White's queenside pawn storm will be faster. } 11. b4 Nf5 12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 h5 14. Qa4 Kb8 *


