1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O? { Premature castling signals a queenside pawn storm coming up } 9... c4! 10. f5 (10. g4 b5 11. Kb1 b4 12. Ne2 { With the same idea as the main variation }) 10... b5! { We reach the same position as seen in Theme #5 above } 11. f6 { An interesting attempt to scrape together some counterplay, but it's harmless in comparison with Black's attack. } (11. Nxb5 Rb8 12. Nd6 Bxd6 13. exd6 Nf6) 11... gxf6 12. Bh6 fxe5 13. dxe5 Ndxe5 14. Bxf8 Bxf8 { Sacrificing the exchange here is wise since the dark squared bishop will now be a menace along the c1-h6 and a1-h8 diagonals while White can barely make use of both rooks. } *


