1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 a6 { The third part is dedicated to the lines where Black plays an early a6, Najdorf style, to prevent Bb5 altogether. I recommend switching to a Maroczy Bind structure with c4 and e4 pawn structure. } 5. h3 { The purpose of an early h3 is to avoid any Bg4 lines where Black exchanges the bishop for White knight. } 5... Nc6 6. Qe3 g6 7. c4 Bg7 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O { It is common to develop the rooks to b1 and d1 to maintain the bind. A well timed c5 or e5 pawn break will suit White well in the middlegames. } 10... Be6 (10... Bd7 11. Rb1 Rc8 12. Rd1) (10... Nd7 11. Rb1 Nde5 12. Rd1 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3) 11. Rb1 Rc8 12. Rd1 { White has completed development. Look for e5 or c5 ideas } *


